Since I was a little kid in my dad’s shop I have been experimenting with tools and materials. Learning how to use and implement them. Now 40+ years later that’s all I have been doing: Making things and teaching how to make things involving metal, wood, plastic and more.

I have been making things ever since I was able to hold a hammer and likely longer than that. I grew up working around, and alongside my dad, a Long Island handyman.  He put me in an environment to keep experimenting  and learning, so my early education involved a wide array of problem solving using all manner of tools, skills and materials… and that is my philosophy in the shop; learn all you can about anything and everything so it becomes a part of your problem solving arsenal.

ICE PICK PRODUCTION: STEP 1 - The Squish
The first step in preparing the sheath tube's solder joint to the ring is creating a flat on one end of the tube and sanding it square. 

Buy your very own @jimmydiresta Ice Pick from imakeny.com !

#IcePick #Diresta #Brass #EDC #IMake #direstaicepick

ICE PICK PRODUCTION: STEP 2 - Ring Sanding

The next step in preparation for soldering is sanding a flat spot on the ring. Ideally, this flat spot is the width of the flat on our sheath tube for a maximum bonding surface. 

To get your very own @jimmydiresta Ice Pick, go to imakeny.com ! 

#IcePick #Diresta #IMake #JimmyDiresta #DirestaIcePick

P.S. This video is not sped up in any way. I'm just lightning fast⚡️

ICE PICK PRODUCTION: STEP 3 - Solder

Our parts are ready to be joined with low melt point silver solder. The parts are placed in the jig, fluxed at the joint, with one piece of solder the length of the joint and are heated with mapp gas torches. As the solder heats up, it forms into a liquid ball and the torches are moved from top and bottom. The solder is drawn to heat, so we keep our bottom torch closer to the joint in order to wick the solder through the joint, ensuring a strong bond. The Ice Pick sheath is now dropped into an acid bath to clean off the remaining flux. 

To get your very own @jimmydiresta Ice Pick, go to imakeny.com ! 

#IcePick #Diresta #IMake #JimmyDiresta #DirestaIcePick

ICE PICK PRODUCTION: STEP 4 - Dink

Perhaps the whackiest machine of the bunch, we call this one, "The Dinker." One of the most crucial parts that make the ice pick sheath stay on your ice pick is its spring tension that holds onto the ice pick itself. The "Dink" is essentially a punched dimple in the tube that restricts the opening of the sheath tube, making it impossible for the ice pick to enter the tube. The next step, step 5, will help to alleviate that restricted opening while maintaining the necessary spring-loaded pressure to keep the sheath on the ice pick. 

Comment below what you think the "Dinker" originally was before it was made into the contraption it is today.
(Hint: The rocker arm up top was NOT original to the machine)

ANSWER: a very precise Watch Makers Drill press!

To get your very own @jimmydiresta Ice Pick, go to imakeny.com ! 

#IcePick #Diresta #IMake #JimmyDiresta #DirestaIcePick

ICE PICK PRODUCTION: STEP 5 - Slot

The second most crucial step that make the ice pick sheath stay on your ice pick is the "slot." The slot works in conjunction with the "dink" to make our psring action holding pressure. This little slotting saw blade we use to make the slot has made each and every ice pick since day one, therefore, oil is used on each and every tube to keep the blade cool and sharp so we can continue to use it on every ice pick moving forward. A true testament to the tool! 

To get your very own @jimmydiresta Ice Pick, go to imakeny.com ! 

#IcePick #Diresta #IMake #JimmyDiresta #DirestaIcePick

The bandsaw cowboys…🤠🤠🤠

Who do I talk to about joining your gang? @jimmydiresta @davebauerart @shawnbbeckner @00schralf @jeremyspecce 

#bandsawcowboy #bandsawcowboyseason2 #diy #bandsaw #maker #makersgonnamake #jimmydiresta

ICE PICK PRODUCTION: STEP 6 - Polish

Our ice pick sheaths are now wire wheeled at the ring and our tube polished by a blue scotch brite belt. The red ice pick seen in the video used on the @ameribrade belt grinder is a smaller diameter pick in order to allow the finished sheath to spin freely on its shaft, polishing it to perfection. They are placed directly onto a polished ice pick with the DIRESTA stamp, packaged, and sent right to your door. 

To get your very own @jimmydiresta Ice Pick, go to imakeny.com !

Hard to put into words what this man has done for me.  Sure I’ve spent the past decade learning all the skills he’s shown.  As time went on I’d realize how much this man would inspire me to just jump in and try anything.  I’ve watched him come from a tiny flooded basement shop and grow to inspiring a giant community of makers.  I had no idea he would move so many people back then but looking back I think how could he have not.  Jimmy’s secret is he really does love everyone around him.  He wears his heart on his sleeve and that’s what makes him my hero.  I’ve met so many new friends.  Some that would just randomly message me on how inspirational he is or how they love his icepick and they always keep it beside them.  Sometimes 
I even get a screen grab of him following you back.  That’s the type of person he is.  Where a simple follow back can inspire you to change your stars.  That’s exactly why he’s my hero.  Not just because he makes great stuff but because his kindness ignites a light in others and he does it for no reason but just to watch them glow.  When you think you have lost faith in humanity just look to him and you’ll understand that if you have a big heart don’t be afraid to let the world see it.

-The greatest thing Jimmy has done for me…is to believe in me.-

I’ve often been asked how I got into woodworking, but I’ve hardly ever been asked what/who inspired me to share my “I MAKE” journey with you on social (and soon to be on YouTube). There’s a simple answer to that question…Jimmy Diresta 👊🏼

At 9, I remember asking my parents if I could have an IG account. They asked me why, but the only thing I remember from that conversation was talking about Jimmy and saying that I want to be like him. They agreed and I launched Evan’s Workshop on IG in 2018.

It was only fitting that this night happened while I was @themakercamp All I was thinking about as I neared Jimmy’s place was, “is this really happening? Am I about to hang with Jimmy in his own workshop?” Pure magic! 

I’m grateful that we got to spend time together and just chill 🤙🏼 We have a lot in common, but 3 things that I’m super proud to share with Jimmy is that we both wear our hearts on our sleeve, we have a passion to make and we love to give back to our community. 

You’re a legend, JD,  and I’m grateful for your inspiration and for our friendship. Looking forward to sharing many more experiences with you. 

🛠️⚒️🛠️🪵🪵🪵

Thank you for all the love for our dad, Joe, who passed away on his favorite day of the week, “flea market sunday” 
We are grateful for TONS of love and support. (I’ll reply soon!).

The wake for our dad will be at Towers Funeral Home at 2861 Long Beach Blvd in Oceanside on Friday, Dec 8th from 2-4 pm and 6-9 pm. Funeral service will be at Towers on Saturday morning, Dec 9th at 10:30 am. Memorial luncheon to follow at Knights of Columbus. Hope you can join us and celebrate Joe. We are grateful for all the love ❤️
If you would like to donate on his behalf, visit: https://www.nyffburncenter.com

One of a kind. Generous, sarcastic, and opinionated but most of all a huge heart.
He was so incredibly proud of all of us and we are so lucky.

We grew up with SO many stories of Far Rockaway, the Navy, cousins, working on Wall Street.
His career as a fireman and love of comedy led to @johndiresta being a cop and comedian.
The workshop in the basement, interest in photography, cameras, and tools -led to all of our creative careers. He and our mom always made sure we were creating. 
He started a legacy of makers through @jimmydiresta 
The thrill of the hunt aka garage sales and flea markets were his joy. “One dollar thank YOU”.
While it filled his life beyond measure, it still brought him joy.

He never missed a chance to compliment or mention his grandkids - Aidan, Hunter, Matt, Sabrina, Shannon, Dylan.
He would smile like a little kid watching videos of great-grandson Noah.

Our love of friends and community are a reflection of his huge network of friends, family, and lifelong bonds with the firemen.
His neighbors were always looking out for him. 
Grateful to be surrounded by love in his honor. Thank you ❤️
